In KVM / libvirt, several virtual disk formats are supported beyond qcow2, and the best choice for production depends on your priorities: performance, flexibility, storage backend, and management features.
Common KVM Disk Types
1. raw (Recommended for most production workloads)


Direct block image with no extra metadata


Best performance (lowest overhead)


Supports:


Local files (.img)


LVM logical volumes


Direct SAN/iSCSI/FC LUNs


NVMe devices




Pros:


Fastest I/O


Best for databases and high-performance apps


Easy migration to block storage




Cons:


No built-in snapshots


No compression or thin provisioning




Production use:
Best for performance-critical VMs

2. LVM / LVM-thin


VM disk stored as logical volume


Pros:


Near-raw performance


Centralized storage management


Live migration possible


Thin provisioning with LVM-thin




Cons:


Slightly more management complexity


Thin pools need monitoring




Production use:
Excellent for enterprise virtualization

3. qcow2


Copy-on-write format


Features:


Snapshots


Compression


Encryption


Thin provisioning




Pros:


Flexible


Good for labs/dev/testing




Cons:


Slower than raw


More fragmentation risk




Production use:
Usually avoided for heavy workloads unless snapshots are essential

4. Direct Block Devices


Physical disks or SAN LUNs passed directly


Examples:


/dev/sdb


/dev/mapper/vg_vm/lv_vm100




Pros:


Maximum performance


Enterprise-grade




Cons:


Requires careful storage management




Production use:
Ideal for serious enterprise environments

5. Ceph RBD


Distributed block storage


Pros:


HA


Live migration


Scalability




Cons:


More complex


Network-dependent




Production use:
Excellent for clustered environments

6. Network Storage Backends


NFS


iSCSI


Fibre Channel


GlusterFS


ZFS zvols


Pros:


Shared storage


Migration support




Cons:


Depends on network/storage quality





Recommended Production Choices
Small/Standalone Production
Use:


raw


LVM


LVM-thin (if thin provisioning needed)



Enterprise / Clustered Production
Use:


Direct SAN LUNs


Fibre Channel


iSCSI


Ceph RBD


ZFS zvol



Avoid for Production if:


Heavy DB workload on qcow2


Large-scale HA with file-based storage unless optimized



